Agent output: Good idea, and now it is set up with a practical workaround.

VS Code cannot directly import one settings file into another, so I implemented a split-source workflow:

1. Pattern source file: [.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json](.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json)
2. Sync script: [.vscode/sync-log-highlighter-patterns.ps1](.vscode/sync-log-highlighter-patterns.ps1)
3. Task to run sync: [.vscode/tasks.json](.vscode/tasks.json)
4. Active settings remain in: [.vscode/settings.json](.vscode/settings.json)

How to use it:

1. Edit only [.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json](.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json) when you want to change highlights.
2. Run task `Sync Log Highlighter Patterns` from Run Task.
3. That updates [.vscode/settings.json](.vscode/settings.json) with the new array.

Validation status:

1. Sync script runs successfully.
2. `logFileHighlighter.customPatterns` is now a proper array.
3. No errors in [.vscode/settings.json](.vscode/settings.json), [.vscode/sync-log-highlighter-patterns.ps1](.vscode/sync-log-highlighter-patterns.ps1), [.vscode/tasks.json](.vscode/tasks.json), or [.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json](.vscode/logFileHighlighter.customPatterns.json).

